cs.IR, cs.DL, cs.SI, cs.CL, cs.CY

The paper focuses on understanding the mechanisms governing scientific creative processes by analyzing authors' information consumption behaviors and their knowledge products. This aligns with several sub-categories in computer science, including Information Retrieval (cs.IR), Digital Libraries (cs.DL), Social and Information Networks (cs.SI), Computational Linguistics (cs.CL), and Computers and Society (cs.CY). However, given the emphasis on analyzing large-scale datasets and developing predictive frameworks, cs.IR and cs.DL are the most likely sub-categories.
